Government Network and Business Unit Hardening Guidelines

The security of government networks and business units is critical, and adherence to minimum baseline requirements and hardening guidelines is essential. These guidelines provide a framework for establishing a secure network infrastructure, maintaining the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of data and systems, and reducing the risk of cyber-attacks. In this essay, we will identify and explain two auditing frameworks or hardening guidelines/security checklists used by the Department of Defense (DoD).

Auditing Frameworks and Hardening Guidelines used by DoD

    Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) Security Technical Implementation Guides (STIGs)

The Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) Security Technical Implementation Guides (STIGs) are a collection of documents that provide guidelines for securing computer systems and networks. The STIGs outline the minimum security requirements for the deployment of systems and applications, covering all aspects of security, including access control, auditing and logging, configuration management, network security, and vulnerability management. The STIGs are available for a wide range of products, including operating systems, databases, web servers, and other applications. The guidelines are updated frequently and aligned with the latest security standards.

    National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) Special Publication (SP) 800-171

The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) Special Publication (SP) 800-171 provides guidelines for protecting the confidentiality of Controlled Unclassified Information (CUI) in nonfederal information systems and organizations. The guideline provides a framework of 14 control families that cover all aspects of security, including access control, awareness and training, configuration management, incident response, and network security. Compliance with NIST SP 800-171 is mandatory for all non-federal organizations that process, store or transmit CUI.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the DoD provides various auditing frameworks and hardening guidelines that provide a framework for securing government networks and business units. The DISA Security Technical Implementation Guides (STIGs) and the NIST Special Publication (SP) 800-171 are two examples of frameworks and guidelines that are available for securing DoD systems and networks. It is essential to adhere to these guidelines to ensure that DoD networks and systems are secure and safeguarded against cyber-attacks.














